body:
Repro steps:

1. Install RC plugin
1. File>Create project, set paths, and ensure everything is open
1. File>Close all open projects
1. Click open, pick <flutter sdk dir>/examples/hello_world/

=> Project load fails:

![screen shot 2017-03-30 at 12 55 54](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/13644170/24501058/3ccb3b3a-1548-11e7-94e8-f2fdfa5521c5.png)

comment_data.body: Reproed on both macOS and Windows.
This is probably the same root issue as #859?
Most likely the cause is different. I guess there's some critical error in logs (Help | Show Log).

This piece of log shows no problems. Pay attention to the recommendations wrt tool window icon size. :)

I could misunderstand the bug report. Is the IDE in an unactionable state? Can you open tool windows, files, preferences, etc.? Or what do you mean by 'project load fails'?

Sorry for being imprecise. Project load doesn't actually fail, it just looks like it (no project view, no file opens, run config has red cross). If you open main.dart you get:

![screen shot 2017-03-30 at 16 21 01](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/13644170/24508799/e3923880-1564-11e7-8ccd-0d26b19ad0ad.png)

If the project has ever been opened before - next time you open it all files and tool windows are restored in the state you left them previous time. However, if you deleted .idea/workspace.xml file then knowledge about tool windows / open files / etc. is lost.

Some of the issues here may have been the intelliJ metadata needing to be updated (https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/9100), and that the workspace files may have been deleted. I am able to open the flutter repo, using these steps:

```shell
git clone https://github.com/flutter/flutter.git
(cd flutter; bin/flutter update-packages)
idea flutter
```

This still does not work for me with these steps:

```
cd tmp
git clone https://github.com/flutter/flutter.git
```

* Start IJ
* File > Open, select `tmp/flutter/examples/hello_world/`
* Open `lib/main.dart`

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/13644170/24660959/410955d0-1951-11e7-902f-5fa44d5c661b.png)

Above steps using IJ on Windows, thus no open from terminal. File > Create a Flutter projects works as expected.

Your initial issue was that the project load fails; it looks like that's not an issue now.

I do see what the same behavior as your latest repro steps. When I set an sdk and run the 'get dependencies' from the editor header, things work as expected.

An enhancement here would be to offer to set the Flutter sdk in the editor header. Perhaps better tracked under https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/issues/535?
No, this is the same issue I saw before, see https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/issues/860#issuecomment-290425712

I don't think this is the same as #535. That is a small enhancement to make the 'File > Open, select example' step easier to perform. This tracks a more concrete issue that we fail to properly load and configure a Flutter project with working analysis from our own examples.

Didn't we add support a few months ago to auto-get dependencies if needed?

Do we also not see the 'No Flutter SDK issue' if you try on Windows?

> Didn't we add support a few months ago to auto-get dependencies if needed?

I don't think so - just displaying the editor header when you need to run flutter packages get.

> Do we also not see the 'No Flutter SDK issue' if you try on Windows?

I don't have a windows machine available at the moment - I'm testing on macos.
Clarifying title to better match https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/issues/860#issuecomment-290425712

This also repros for me on Linux with 2017.1.

I can File > Create projects and things work as expected. But both /examples/hello_world/ and a new project created with `flutter create` lead to the not Dart + Flutter SDK banners when `lib/main.dart` is opened.
note to self: we can add the SDK info into the metadata in the repo
@mit-mit can repro on the mac.
For at least @pq and @mit-mit, it looks like the SDK setting is not reliably sticking?

Still repros in 2017.1 on Windows. Clicking the 'Enable Dart' support in the banner was not enough to resolve the issue; you need to manually open settings and set the Flutter SDK.

Interestingly, a new project created with `flutter create` in the command prompt opened just fine!

What example did you try?  @skybrian fixed the metadata in gallery as of https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/9452, so I'd expect that to work.  If it does, we should probably update them all similarly.

I see no difference between opening flutter_gallery and hello_world.

Note: Make sure to test this with a freshly cloned flutter repo.
@mit-mit, did the newly cloned repo have a dart sdk? If you don't run that initial `bin/flutter` script, there will be no dart sdk.

I think Devon's guess is quite likely. We could fix this by running bin/flutter just before opening any Flutter project, to "warm it up" (make sure the Dart SDK exists).

Or perhaps do this whenever the Dart SDK is missing in a Flutter SDK?
@skybrian: would you mind testing the theory?
Yup, I think that is it. Won't be able to re-test until tomorrow though....

If I clone the flutter repo, don't run bin/flutter, and open the project, here's what happens:

 - In Project Structure, there is a problem report: "Library Dart SDK has broken classes paths:" (sic)

If I open lib/main.dart, there are three warnings:

  - Dart SDKis not configured
  - No Flutter SDK configured
  - 'Packages get' has not been run

I'll see what I can do.

I can confirm that opening /examples/flutter_gallery/ works after running the get-packages step.

But looks like we still need to fix each of the other sample apps in /examples/

Great!

@skybrian @devoncarew : any reason not to update all the examples this way?
We'll need to maintain the sdk metadata for each sample. If we do this, we should put in a test so that the build fails if and when the metadata gets out of date.
Sure, updating the samples seems fine.
We have a solution on track for this, but it's probably a bigger change than we want to go into the tail end of M13. Let's publish M13, evaluate the solution, and see if we want it in M14 or a 13.1.
@devoncarew, @skybrian : what's the current thinking on this one?
I'll verify it works.
Opening Flutter Gallery works. The other examples have apparently not been updated. I'll send a patch.
Also, it can be slow depending on the network connection. #992
Other flutter examples patched as of: https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/9847

Sounds like this should be fixed.

@mit-mit  can you verify on your end?

All /examples/ open great now! Thanks!

Closing.
